dowSize(); // Calculate the position of the button ImVec2 buttonPos(windowPos.x + 10, windowPos.y + windowSize.y - 30); ImGui::SetCursorPos(buttonPos); if ( ImGui::Button(\\"Save current Settings\\")) for some reason after using those snippet and creating button on bottom-left side in my imgui window slider appears, and to see that button i should slide window down. changing window size doesnâ€™t fix that","output":"issue. The reason for this behavior is that the button is being placed outside of the visible portion of the ImGui window. The slider appears to allow the user to slide the contents of the window up/down to reveal the button. To fix this, you should adjust the position of the button so that it is completely inside the visible portion of the window. You can do this by modifying the y-coordinate of the buttonPos variable. For example, you can change the line: ImVec2 buttonPos(windowPos.x + 10, windowPos.y + windowSize.y - 30); to: ImVec2 buttonPos(windowPos.x + 10, windowPos.y + windowSize.y - 60); This will place the button 30 pixels higher, so that it is fully visible without the need for scrolling. Adjust the value as needed to position the button where you want it to be."},{"instruction":"when i move window button moves on horizontal directions too","output":"If you are experiencing the issue where the button moves horizontally when you move the window, it is likely because the button position is being calculated based on the window position and size, which are changing when the window is moved. To solve this issue, instead of using `windowPos` to calculate the button position, you can use `ImGui::GetCursorScreenPos()` to get the current position of the ImGui cursor on the screen, and then add an offset to that position to position the button where you want it. Here is an example of how you can modify your code to use `ImGui::GetCursorScreenPos()`: ``` // Get the current cursor position ImVec2 cursorPos = ImGui::GetCursorScreenPos(); // Calculate the position of the button ImVec2 buttonPos(cursorPos.x + 10, cursorPos.y - 30); // Set the cursor position to the button position ImGui::SetCursorScreenPos(buttonPos); // Draw the button if (ImGui::Button(\\"Save current Settings\\")) { // Handle button click } ``` In this example, `cursorPos` is the position of the ImGui cursor on the screen, which does not change when the window is moved. You can then calculate the position of the button relative to the cursor position, and set the cursor position to the button position using `ImGui::SetCursorScreenPos()`. This will ensure that the button is positioned correctly even when the window is moved."},{"instruction":"it\'s still moving when i change windows position","output":"If the button position is still moving when you change the window position, it\'s possible that you are not calculating the position correctly. Here\'s one way to calculate the button position in a way that should be independent of the window position: ``` // Store the size of the main window const ImVec2 mainWindowSize = ImGui::GetMainViewport()->Size; // Calculate the position of the button const ImVec2 buttonSize(ImGui::GetWindowWidth() - 20.f, 30.f); const ImVec2 buttonPosition(mainWindowSize.x - buttonSize.x, mainWindowSize.y - buttonSize.y); // Set the cursor position to the button position ImGui::SetCursorPos(buttonPosition); // Draw the button if (ImGui::Button(\\"Save current Settings\\")) { // Handle button click } ``` In this code, we first store the size of the main window using `ImGui::GetMainViewport()->Size`, which should give us the size of the window independent of its position. We then calculate the position of the button based on the main window size and the size of the button (which we\'ve set to `ImGui::GetWindowWidth() - 20.f` for the x-coordinate, and 30.f for the y-coordinate). We then set the cursor position to the button position using `ImGui::SetCursorPos()`. This should position the button at the bottom-right corner of the window, regardless of where the window is located. If you continue to have problems, it may be helpful to provide more information about the specific behavior you are seeing, as well as any additional code that may be relevant to the problem."},{"instruction":"in that snippet button position located at the bottom of main window, but not imgui current window.","output":"You\'re correct, I apologize for the confusion. The snippet I provided earlier positions the button relative to the main ImGui window, not the current window. To position the button at the bottom-left corner of the current ImGui window, you can use the following modified code: ``` ImVec2 currentWindowPos = ImGui::GetWindowPos(); ImVec2 currentWindowSize = ImGui::GetWindowSize(); ImVec2 buttonSize(currentWindowSize.x, 30.f); ImVec2 buttonPos(currentWindowPos.x, currentWindowPos.y + currentWindowSize.y - buttonSize.y); ImGui::SetCursorPos(buttonPos); if (ImGui::Button(\\"Save current Settings\\")) { // Handle button click } ``` In this code, we first retrieve the position and size of the current ImGui window using `ImGui::GetWindowPos()` and `ImGui::GetWindowSize()`, respectively. We then calculate the position of the button based on the current window\'s position, size, and the desired button height. The `buttonSize` variable is set to the width of the current window and the desired button height (in this case, 30 pixels). The `buttonPos` variable is set to the x-coordinate of the current window\'s position and the y-coordinate of the bottom of the window minus the button height. We then set the cursor position to `buttonPos` using `ImGui::SetCursorPos()`, and draw the button using `ImGui::Button()`. This should position the button at the bottom-left corner of the current ImGui window, and should not be affected by changes to the main window position."},{"instruction":"i still have slider and buttons are visible only after using it. how to remove slider and let button be on the bottom edge","output":"If